SIMPLE: upright
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Upright
<hw>Up"right`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>upright</ets>, <ets>uppriht</ets>. See <er>Up</er>, and
<er>Right</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>In an erect
position or posture; perpendicular; vertical, or nearly vertical;
pointing upward; <as>as, an <ex>upright</ex> tree</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With chattering teeth, and bristling hair <qex>upright</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All have their ears <qex>upright</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Morally erect; having rectitude; honest; just;
<as>as, a man <ex>upright</ex> in all his ways</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And that man [Job] was perfect and <qex>upright</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Job i. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Conformable to moral rectitude.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Conscience rewards <qex>upright</qex> conduct with pleasure.</q>
<rj><qau>J. M. Mason.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Stretched out face upward; flat on the back.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧ He lay <xex>upright</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Golf)</fld> <def>Designating a club in which the
head is approximately at a right angle with the shaft.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Upright drill</b></col> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>a
drilling machine having the spindle vertical.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ This word and its derivatives are usually pronounced in
prose with the accent on the first syllable. But they are frequently
pronounced with the accent on the second in poetry, and the accent on
either syllable is admissible.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Upright</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Upright
<hw>Up"right`</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Something standing
upright, as a piece of timber in a building. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of
<er>Frame</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Basketwork)</fld> <def>A tool made from a flat
strip of steel with chisel edges at both ends, bent into horseshoe, the
opening between the cutting edges being adjustable, used for reducing
splits to skeins. Called in full <altname>upright
shave</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Football)</fld> <def>the vertical part of a
goalpost, especially the part above the horizontal bar; <as>as, a field
goal directly between the <ex>uprights</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Uprighteously</ent>⟦br⟧
